1
00:02:07,795 --> 00:02:09,213
Still got it.

2
00:04:41,908 --> 00:04:43,367
<i>What's that?</i>

3
00:04:43,993 --> 00:04:45,828
An old friend.

4
00:04:47,580 --> 00:04:49,999
I was rummaging through a closet...

5
00:04:50,291 --> 00:04:51,709
...and it was sitting there.

6
00:04:51,918 --> 00:04:53,795
It's nice, Paul.

7
00:04:54,003 --> 00:04:55,505
It's got character.

8
00:04:55,713 --> 00:04:57,882
When I wrote my first book,
I carried it...

9
00:04:58,049 --> 00:05:00,343
...in this while I looked
for a publisher.

10
00:05:00,551 --> 00:05:03,429
- I was a writer then.
- You're still a writer.

11
00:05:03,638 --> 00:05:06,390
I haven't been one since I got
in the Misery business.

12
00:05:06,682 --> 00:05:08,267
Not a bad business.

13
00:05:08,476 --> 00:05:11,062
And it would still be growing too.

14
00:05:11,229 --> 00:05:14,398
The first printing for Misery's Child
was the most ever.

15
00:05:14,607 --> 00:05:15,733
{\an8}Over a million.

16
00:05:16,067 --> 00:05:17,568
{\an8}Marcia, please.

17
00:05:18,069 --> 00:05:22,073
Misery Chastain put braces on your
daughter and put her through college.

18
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:24,575
Bought you two houses
and seats to the Knicks.

19
00:05:24,742 --> 00:05:27,119
What thanks does she get?
You go and kill her.

20
00:05:27,537 --> 00:05:30,164
I never meant for it to become my life.

21
00:05:30,706 --> 00:05:32,708
If I hadn't gotten rid of her now...

22
00:05:32,917 --> 00:05:34,961
...I would be
writing her forever.

23
00:05:35,169 --> 00:05:38,840
I'm leaving for Colorado to
try to finish the new book.

24
00:05:39,465 --> 00:05:41,425
If I can make this work...

25
00:05:41,884 --> 00:05:45,388
...I might just have something
I want on my tombstone.

26
00:07:04,884 --> 00:07:07,178
I'm your number one fan.

27
00:07:07,845 --> 00:07:10,598
There's nothing to worry about.

28
00:07:10,806 --> 00:07:13,351
You're gonna be just fine.

29
00:07:13,517 --> 00:07:15,811
I'll take good care of you.

30
00:07:16,312 --> 00:07:18,564
I'm your number one fan.

31
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:29,533
Where am I?

32
00:07:31,202 --> 00:07:33,329
We're just outside Silver Creek.

33
00:07:36,248 --> 00:07:37,583
How long?

34
00:07:37,875 --> 00:07:39,877
You've been here two days.

35
00:07:40,127 --> 00:07:42,088
It's gonna be okay.

36
00:07:43,089 --> 00:07:44,715
My name is Annie Wilkes.

37
00:07:44,882 --> 00:07:46,884
My number one fan.

38
00:07:47,885 --> 00:07:49,929
Yes. That's right.

39
00:07:50,137 --> 00:07:52,014
I'm also a nurse.

40
00:07:53,975 --> 00:07:55,142
Here.

41
00:07:55,393 --> 00:07:56,602
Take these.

42
00:08:27,383 --> 00:08:28,551
Here.

43
00:08:30,302 --> 00:08:31,137
What are they?

44
00:08:31,345 --> 00:08:33,973
They're called Novril.
They're for your pain.

45
00:08:46,110 --> 00:08:47,319
Thank you.

46
00:08:55,327 --> 00:08:57,121
How come I'm not in hospital?

47
00:08:57,538 --> 00:09:00,958
The blizzard was too strong.
I couldn't risk getting you there.

48
00:09:01,125 --> 00:09:03,794
I tried calling,
but the phone lines are down.

49
00:09:05,838 --> 00:09:07,798
You mustn't tire yourself.

50
00:09:08,049 --> 00:09:09,925
You've gotta rest.

51
00:09:10,468 --> 00:09:12,303
You almost died.

52
00:09:24,148 --> 00:09:26,150
Open wide.

53
00:09:31,447 --> 00:09:35,034
Your legs just sing grand opera
when you move, don't they?

54
00:09:35,785 --> 00:09:38,662
It's not gonna hurt forever, Paul.
I promise you.

55
00:09:40,039 --> 00:09:41,624
Will I be able to walk?

56
00:09:41,832 --> 00:09:43,000
Of course you will.

57
00:09:43,209 --> 00:09:45,294
And your arm will be fine too.

58
00:09:45,586 --> 00:09:47,671
Your shoulder was pretty badly dislocated.

59
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:51,050
It was a little stubborn,
but I finally popped it back in.

60
00:09:51,258 --> 00:09:53,803
What I'm proud of
is the work on those legs.

61
00:09:54,220 --> 00:09:58,140
Considering what I had in the house,
a doctor couldn't have done better.

62
00:10:02,853 --> 00:10:05,106
It's not nearly as bad as it looks.

63
00:10:05,314 --> 00:10:08,359
You have a compound fracture
of the tibia in both legs...

64
00:10:08,526 --> 00:10:11,237
...and the fibula in the right leg
is fractured too.

65
00:10:11,529 --> 00:10:13,197
I could hear the bones moving...

66
00:10:13,405 --> 00:10:15,866
...so it's best your legs
remain immobile.

67
00:10:16,408 --> 00:10:18,119
As soon as the roads open...

68
00:10:18,327 --> 00:10:20,287
...I'll take you to a hospital.

69
00:10:20,538 --> 00:10:23,499
In the meantime, you've got a lot of
recovering to do...

70
00:10:23,707 --> 00:10:27,211
...and I consider it an honor
that you'll do it in my home.

71
00:10:35,177 --> 00:10:37,847
This is Marcia Sindell.
I'm calling from New York.

72
00:10:38,055 --> 00:10:40,975
I'd like to speak to the
chief of police or sheriff.

73
00:10:41,183 --> 00:10:43,853
- Which one do you want?
- Whichever one is not busy.

74
00:10:44,061 --> 00:10:48,732
I'm pretty sure they're both not busy,
Ms. Sindell, since they're both me.

75
00:10:48,941 --> 00:10:53,487
I also happen to be president of the
Policeman's Benefit Association...

76
00:10:53,696 --> 00:10:56,115
...chairman of the Patrolman's
Retirement Fund...

77
00:10:56,323 --> 00:10:59,660
...and if you need a fishing
guide, you could do a lot worse.

78
00:10:59,869 --> 00:11:02,288
Call me Buster, everybody does.

79
00:11:02,496 --> 00:11:03,998
What can I do for you?

80
00:11:04,206 --> 00:11:06,250
I'm a literary agent, and I...

81
00:11:06,417 --> 00:11:09,003
I feel like a fool calling you...

82
00:11:09,336 --> 00:11:13,674
...but I think one of my clients,
Paul Sheldon, might be in trouble.

83
00:11:14,258 --> 00:11:17,011
You mean Paul Sheldon the writer?

84
00:11:17,219 --> 00:11:19,597
- He's your client, huh?
- Yes, he is.

85
00:11:19,763 --> 00:11:22,474
Everybody sure likes those Misery books.

86
00:11:22,892 --> 00:11:23,726
Yeah.

87
00:11:23,934 --> 00:11:27,021
I'm sure you know Paul's been
coming to Silver Creek Lodge...

88
00:11:27,229 --> 00:11:28,939
...for years to finish his books.

89
00:11:29,148 --> 00:11:31,942
I understand he's been up here
the last six weeks.

90
00:11:32,109 --> 00:11:33,611
Well, not quite.

91
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:36,280
I just called there and they...

92
00:11:36,739 --> 00:11:39,241
...said he checked out
last Tuesday.

93
00:11:39,450 --> 00:11:40,951
Isn't that a little strange?

94
00:11:41,118 --> 00:11:45,122
I don't know. Does he usually phone
you before he checks out of a hotel?

95
00:11:45,956 --> 00:11:48,000
No. No, of course not.

96
00:11:48,209 --> 00:11:50,711
His daughter hasn't heard from him...

97
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:54,131
...and when he has a book coming out,
he keeps in touch.

98
00:11:54,506 --> 00:11:57,092
So when there wasn't any word
from him, I...

99
00:11:57,301 --> 00:11:59,261
You think he might be missing, huh?

100
00:12:00,638 --> 00:12:04,266
I hate that I made this call.
Tell me I'm being silly.

101
00:12:04,808 --> 00:12:07,728
Oh, a little over-protective maybe.

102
00:12:07,811 --> 00:12:09,813
Tell you what I'll do.

103
00:12:09,980 --> 00:12:12,483
Nothing's been reported out here...

104
00:12:12,816 --> 00:12:15,319
...but I'll put his name
through our system.

105
00:12:16,070 --> 00:12:19,156
If anything turns up,
I'll call you right back.

106
00:12:19,323 --> 00:12:21,533
Oh, I'd appreciate that.
Thanks a lot.

107
00:12:21,742 --> 00:12:23,786
Goodbye, Ms. Sindell.

108
00:12:24,912 --> 00:12:27,748
We got a phone call?
Busy morning.

109
00:12:27,957 --> 00:12:30,000
Yeah. Work, work, work.

110
00:12:30,876 --> 00:12:33,170
Virginia, when was that blizzard?

111
00:12:34,004 --> 00:12:36,548
Last Tuesday. Why?

112
00:12:37,508 --> 00:12:39,176
No reason.

113
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:52,231
I guess it was kind of a miracle,
you finding me.

114
00:12:53,857 --> 00:12:56,318
No, it wasn't a miracle at all.

115
00:12:57,027 --> 00:12:59,363
In a way, I was following you.

116
00:12:59,530 --> 00:13:00,447
Following me?

117
00:13:00,656 --> 00:13:03,951
It wasn't any secret to me you
were at the Silver Creek...

118
00:13:04,159 --> 00:13:06,829
...seeing as how I'm your
number one fan and all.

119
00:13:07,579 --> 00:13:11,208
Some nights I'd just tool on
down there and sit outside...

120
00:13:11,375 --> 00:13:13,752
...and look up at the light
in your cabin...

121
00:13:14,211 --> 00:13:17,881
...and imagine what was going on
in the room of the greatest writer.

122
00:13:18,048 --> 00:13:19,717
Say it again.
I didn't hear you.

123
00:13:19,883 --> 00:13:21,218
Don't move now.

124
00:13:21,385 --> 00:13:23,512
I wouldn't want to hurt this neck.

125
00:13:25,222 --> 00:13:27,099
Well, the other afternoon...

126
00:13:27,308 --> 00:13:29,351
...I was on my way home...

127
00:13:29,560 --> 00:13:32,229
...and there you were,
leaving the lodge.

128
00:13:32,396 --> 00:13:37,151
I wondered why a literary genius would
go out when there was a storm coming.

129
00:13:37,484 --> 00:13:39,903
I didn't know there was
a big storm coming.

130
00:13:40,070 --> 00:13:41,739
Lucky for you I did.

131
00:13:41,905 --> 00:13:43,741
Lucky for me too.

132
00:13:43,949 --> 00:13:45,743
Because now you're alive...

133
00:13:45,951 --> 00:13:48,329
...and you can write more books.

134
00:13:48,662 --> 00:13:51,123
Oh, Paul, I've read everything of yours.

135
00:13:51,248 --> 00:13:53,834
The Misery novels.
I know them all by heart.

136
00:13:53,917 --> 00:13:57,004
All eight of them.
I love them so.

137
00:13:57,504 --> 00:13:58,756
You're very kind.

138
00:13:58,964 --> 00:14:00,924
And you're very brilliant.

139
00:14:02,343 --> 00:14:04,011
Like a baby.

140
00:14:04,303 --> 00:14:06,180
- All done.
- Thank you.

141
00:14:07,639 --> 00:14:09,892
When do you think
the phone lines will be up?

142
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:12,686
I have to call my daughter
and agent in New York...

143
00:14:12,895 --> 00:14:14,605
...to let her know I'm alive.

144
00:14:14,813 --> 00:14:16,482
It shouldn't be much longer.

145
00:14:16,690 --> 00:14:19,818
Once the roads open, the phone
lines will be up in no time.

146
00:14:20,027 --> 00:14:23,072
If you give me their numbers,
I'll keep trying them.

147
00:14:25,574 --> 00:14:27,368
Could I ask you a favor?

148
00:14:30,079 --> 00:14:33,957
I noticed in your case there is
a new Paul Sheldon book...

149
00:14:34,666 --> 00:14:36,627
...and I wondered if maybe...

150
00:14:37,002 --> 00:14:38,212
You want to read it?

151
00:14:38,837 --> 00:14:41,048
If you wouldn't mind.

152
00:14:41,632 --> 00:14:43,300
I have a hard and fast rule...

153
00:14:43,467 --> 00:14:46,095
...as to who reads my stuff
at this early stage.

154
00:14:46,804 --> 00:14:49,139
Only my editor, my agent...

155
00:14:49,306 --> 00:14:52,810
...and anybody who saves me from
freezing to death in a car wreck.

156
00:15:00,401 --> 00:15:04,238
You'll never realize
what a rare treat you've given me.

157
00:15:06,407 --> 00:15:10,369
Boy, it's like clockwork,
the way your pain comes.

158
00:15:10,577 --> 00:15:13,163
I'll get your Novril.
Forgive me for prattling...

159
00:15:13,372 --> 00:15:15,624
...and making you feel all oogy.

160
00:15:20,170 --> 00:15:22,339
What's your new book called?

161
00:15:22,923 --> 00:15:24,800
I don't have a title yet.

162
00:15:25,217 --> 00:15:26,969
What's it about?

163
00:15:27,886 --> 00:15:29,346
I don't know.

164
00:15:29,805 --> 00:15:32,141
I know it sounds crazy, but I haven't...

165
00:15:32,349 --> 00:15:34,893
...written anything but Misery
for so long.

166
00:15:35,102 --> 00:15:36,687
Why don't you read it...

167
00:15:37,855 --> 00:15:39,731
...and tell me what it's about.

168
00:15:39,940 --> 00:15:41,859
Maybe you can come up with a title.

169
00:15:43,110 --> 00:15:45,237
Like I could do that.

170
00:15:48,031 --> 00:15:51,535
Nothing unusual about
Mr. Sheldon's leaving, Buster.

171
00:15:51,743 --> 00:15:54,705
- You can tell by the champagne.
- Maybe you can, Libby.

172
00:15:54,913 --> 00:15:58,959
He always orders a bottle of
Dom Perignon when he's ready to go.

173
00:15:59,168 --> 00:16:01,044
Then he pays up and he's out.

174
00:16:01,253 --> 00:16:03,505
No long-distance phone calls...

175
00:16:03,714 --> 00:16:05,466
...or Federal Express packages?

176
00:16:05,674 --> 00:16:07,759
Anything out of the ordinary?

177
00:16:08,343 --> 00:16:12,347
I don't think Mr. Sheldon likes for
things to be out of the ordinary.

178
00:16:12,556 --> 00:16:15,851
Considering who he is,
and all famous and all...

179
00:16:16,226 --> 00:16:18,896
...he doesn't put on airs.

180
00:16:19,104 --> 00:16:22,524
Drives up from New York
in the same car each time.

181
00:16:22,733 --> 00:16:26,320
A '65 Mustang.
Says it helps him to think.

182
00:16:27,571 --> 00:16:29,198
Always been a good guest.

183
00:16:29,406 --> 00:16:31,492
Never makes a noise.
Never bothers a soul.

184
00:16:32,951 --> 00:16:36,246
- I hope nothing's happened to him.
- So do I.

185
00:16:36,663 --> 00:16:39,958
I bet that old Mustang's pulling into
New York right now.

186
00:16:41,335 --> 00:16:43,670
I'm sure you're right.
Thanks, Libby.

187
00:16:43,879 --> 00:16:45,255
My pleasure.

188
00:16:58,977 --> 00:17:02,856
I know I'm only 40 pages
into your book, but...

189
00:17:04,691 --> 00:17:05,943
But what?

190
00:17:07,819 --> 00:17:08,904
Nothing.

191
00:17:09,112 --> 00:17:10,113
No, no.

192
00:17:10,280 --> 00:17:11,365
What is it?

193
00:17:12,658 --> 00:17:14,117
What's ridiculous...

194
00:17:14,326 --> 00:17:17,079
Who am I to make a criticism
to someone like you?

195
00:17:17,287 --> 00:17:19,289
It's all right, I can take it.

196
00:17:22,417 --> 00:17:23,961
It's brilliantly written.

197
00:17:24,169 --> 00:17:26,630
But then everything you write
is brilliant.

198
00:17:26,922 --> 00:17:28,715
Pretty rough stuff, huh?

199
00:17:30,634 --> 00:17:32,511
The swearing, Paul.

200
00:17:34,638 --> 00:17:36,306
There, I said it.

201
00:17:37,307 --> 00:17:39,977
Yeah. The profanity bothers you.

202
00:17:40,269 --> 00:17:41,853
It has no nobility.

203
00:17:42,646 --> 00:17:44,606
These are slum kids.

204
00:17:44,690 --> 00:17:46,525
I was a slum kid.

205
00:17:46,984 --> 00:17:48,485
Everybody talks like that.

206
00:17:48,652 --> 00:17:50,445
They do not!

207
00:17:50,696 --> 00:17:52,906
What do you think I say at the feed store?

208
00:17:53,115 --> 00:17:56,702
"Now Wally, give a bag of that
effing pig feed and...

209
00:17:56,910 --> 00:17:59,538
...ten pounds of that
bitchly cow corn!"

210
00:17:59,746 --> 00:18:02,291
And the bank.
Do I tell Mrs. Bollinger:

211
00:18:02,499 --> 00:18:04,459
"Here's one big bastard of a check...

212
00:18:04,668 --> 00:18:06,378
...give me your Christing money!"

213
00:18:06,587 --> 00:18:08,046
There! Look there!

214
00:18:08,255 --> 00:18:10,048
See what you made me do?!

215
00:18:14,386 --> 00:18:16,888
Oh, Paul, I'm sorry.

216
00:18:17,347 --> 00:18:19,433
I'm so sorry.

217
00:18:24,354 --> 00:18:26,607
Sometimes I get so worked up.

218
00:18:27,399 --> 00:18:29,443
Can you ever forgive me?

219
00:18:30,527 --> 00:18:32,571
It's fine.

220
00:18:38,076 --> 00:18:39,995
I love you, Paul.

221
00:18:43,832 --> 00:18:45,208
Your mind.

222
00:18:45,375 --> 00:18:48,545
Your creativity.
That's all I meant.

223
00:19:28,794 --> 00:19:30,629
Well, this sure is fun.

224
00:19:41,932 --> 00:19:42,974
Virginia...

225
00:19:43,183 --> 00:19:47,145
...when you're in this car,
you're not my wife, you're my deputy.

226
00:19:48,438 --> 00:19:52,275
This deputy would rather be home
under the covers with the sheriff.

227
00:19:53,985 --> 00:19:54,945
- Stop.
- What?

228
00:19:55,112 --> 00:19:57,030
- Stop!
- What?

229
00:20:07,624 --> 00:20:09,501
See that broken limb?

230
00:20:10,377 --> 00:20:12,003
Could be the weight of the snow.

231
00:20:12,212 --> 00:20:15,382
Could have been a rotten branch,
could have been the wind.

232
00:20:15,590 --> 00:20:17,551
Could have been a lot of things.

233
00:20:52,669 --> 00:20:54,713
Need some help?

234
00:20:55,464 --> 00:20:57,841
No, I'm enjoying myself!

235
00:20:58,049 --> 00:20:59,384
Thank you.

236
00:21:20,322 --> 00:21:22,240
You think Sheldon's out there?

237
00:21:22,449 --> 00:21:23,950
I hope not.

238
00:21:24,201 --> 00:21:26,077
If he is, he's dead.

239
00:21:26,620 --> 00:21:29,039
Let's go to the newspaper office.

240
00:22:01,571 --> 00:22:03,532
Oh, I hope I didn't wake you.

241
00:22:05,242 --> 00:22:07,202
No, it's fine.

242
00:22:09,079 --> 00:22:10,914
{\an8}Look what I got.

243
00:22:11,122 --> 00:22:14,209
{\an8}They had it at the store.
There was a whole batch of them.

244
00:22:14,417 --> 00:22:18,547
As soon as I saw it, I slammed my
money down. I got the first copy.

245
00:22:18,755 --> 00:22:20,048
Then the roads are open.

246
00:22:20,257 --> 00:22:22,634
The one to town is, but that's about it.

247
00:22:22,843 --> 00:22:26,513
I called the hospital and I talked
to the head orthopedic surgeon...

248
00:22:26,721 --> 00:22:29,641
...and I told him who you were
and what had happened.

249
00:22:29,850 --> 00:22:32,936
And he said as long as
there's no infection...

250
00:22:33,103 --> 00:22:34,437
...you're not in danger.

251
00:22:34,604 --> 00:22:39,192
As soon as the road to the hospital
is open, they'll send an ambulance.

252
00:22:39,401 --> 00:22:40,735
The phone's working?

253
00:22:42,529 --> 00:22:43,738
Mine's still out.

254
00:22:43,947 --> 00:22:46,199
The ones in town were working just fine.

255
00:22:46,408 --> 00:22:48,118
I called that agent of yours.

256
00:22:48,326 --> 00:22:51,454
Oh, Paul, I peeked at the very beginning.

257
00:22:51,663 --> 00:22:53,498
What a wonderful first page.

258
00:22:53,707 --> 00:22:56,626
- The name Misery Chastain.
- My daughter must be going nuts.

259
00:22:56,793 --> 00:22:58,044
Like a visit from my--

260
00:22:58,253 --> 00:23:01,464
I'm supposed to be home
for her birthday. It's today.

261
00:23:03,800 --> 00:23:06,636
The agent said she would tell her.
You'll have to wait...

262
00:23:06,803 --> 00:23:09,723
...till tomorrow if you
want to talk to her yourself.

263
00:23:13,184 --> 00:23:14,686
Oh, Paul...

264
00:23:15,395 --> 00:23:17,480
...what a poet you are.

265
00:23:26,156 --> 00:23:27,824
I made you my specialty:

266
00:23:28,033 --> 00:23:30,327
Scrambled eggs à la Wilkes.

267
00:23:30,785 --> 00:23:33,288
And I'm on page 75.

268
00:23:34,039 --> 00:23:36,708
I guess that means it's okay.

269
00:23:36,917 --> 00:23:38,168
No.

270
00:23:38,835 --> 00:23:40,712
No, it isn't. It's...

271
00:23:41,421 --> 00:23:42,422
Oh, pooh.

272
00:23:42,631 --> 00:23:44,841
I can't think of any words.

273
00:23:44,883 --> 00:23:46,593
Would "great" be insulting?

274
00:23:48,178 --> 00:23:49,888
I can live with "great."

275
00:23:50,347 --> 00:23:51,890
No.

276
00:23:52,724 --> 00:23:55,268
It's not just great, it's...

277
00:23:56,645 --> 00:23:57,687
...perfect.

278
00:23:59,981 --> 00:24:02,442
A perfect, perfect thing.

279
00:24:49,239 --> 00:24:51,825
I thought it was time you two should meet.

280
00:24:52,701 --> 00:24:55,954
Paul, say hello to my favorite
beast in the whole world.

281
00:24:56,079 --> 00:24:57,914
My sow, Misery.

282
00:24:59,624 --> 00:25:00,542
Misery?

283
00:25:00,750 --> 00:25:03,294
Yes. I told you
I was your number one fan.

284
00:25:03,795 --> 00:25:05,255
Yeah, I'm...

285
00:25:05,422 --> 00:25:07,132
...starting to believe you.

286
00:25:07,340 --> 00:25:10,760
This farm was dreary, what with
a few cows and chickens and me.

287
00:25:10,969 --> 00:25:14,097
But when I got Misery here,
everything changed.

288
00:25:14,305 --> 00:25:16,599
She just makes me smile so.

289
00:25:16,808 --> 00:25:18,727
She's a fine...

290
00:25:19,519 --> 00:25:21,187
...pig, is what she is.

291
00:25:23,523 --> 00:25:25,984
I'm on page 300 now, Paul.

292
00:25:26,401 --> 00:25:28,069
And it's better than perfect.

293
00:25:28,361 --> 00:25:30,238
It's divine.

294
00:25:30,780 --> 00:25:32,991
What's the ceiling that dago painted?

295
00:25:33,950 --> 00:25:35,493
The Sistine Chapel.

296
00:25:35,702 --> 00:25:36,619
Yeah.

297
00:25:36,786 --> 00:25:38,747
That and Misery's Child.

298
00:25:38,955 --> 00:25:42,959
Those are the only two divine
things ever in this world.

299
00:26:00,894 --> 00:26:04,105
When my husband left me,
I wasn't prepared.

300
00:26:05,231 --> 00:26:07,317
It wasn't an easy time.

301
00:26:08,985 --> 00:26:11,738
For a while I thought I might go crazy.

302
00:26:13,156 --> 00:26:15,325
I know how that can be.

303
00:26:17,660 --> 00:26:19,412
I don't know about you...

304
00:26:19,621 --> 00:26:22,832
...but what I did to get through it
was I dove into work.

305
00:26:23,208 --> 00:26:25,168
Days, nights.

306
00:26:26,920 --> 00:26:29,714
Night shifts can be lonely at a hospital.

307
00:26:30,548 --> 00:26:32,550
I did a lot of reading.

308
00:26:33,718 --> 00:26:36,513
That was when I first discovered Misery.

309
00:26:37,347 --> 00:26:39,599
She made me so happy.

310
00:26:40,058 --> 00:26:43,019
She made me forget all my problems.

311
00:26:44,187 --> 00:26:47,524
Of course, you had a little
something to do with that too.

312
00:26:47,774 --> 00:26:49,692
Yeah, well...

313
00:26:52,779 --> 00:26:55,490
I just kept reading them over and over.

314
00:26:56,116 --> 00:26:58,785
I've only got two chapters left
and when I finish...

315
00:26:58,993 --> 00:27:00,703
...I'll turn to the first page...

316
00:27:00,870 --> 00:27:03,373
...and start reading it
all over again.

317
00:27:04,499 --> 00:27:05,959
I'm, uh...

318
00:27:09,379 --> 00:27:11,131
- Done?
- Yeah.

319
00:27:11,339 --> 00:27:12,882
No problem.

320
00:27:14,717 --> 00:27:16,052
Thanks.

321
00:27:16,511 --> 00:27:17,679
Don't get me wrong.

322
00:27:17,887 --> 00:27:20,390
I'm not against marriage per se, but...

323
00:27:20,557 --> 00:27:24,644
...it'd take a special guy to make me
want to walk down that aisle again.

324
00:27:25,019 --> 00:27:28,398
Yeah, it's not something you
should enter into lightly.

325
00:27:28,773 --> 00:27:31,067
It boils down to respect.

326
00:27:31,234 --> 00:27:34,154
People don't respect the
institution of marriage anymore.

327
00:27:34,362 --> 00:27:36,865
They have no sense of real commitment.

328
00:27:39,909 --> 00:27:40,910
Well...

329
00:27:41,077 --> 00:27:43,580
...I'd love to chat,
but I'm right at the end...

330
00:27:43,788 --> 00:27:46,249
...and I gotta find out what happens.

331
00:28:08,104 --> 00:28:09,439
You.

332
00:28:11,941 --> 00:28:13,109
You...

333
00:28:13,276 --> 00:28:14,777
...dirty bird.

334
00:28:14,944 --> 00:28:16,487
How could you?

335
00:28:17,780 --> 00:28:19,949
She can't be dead.

336
00:28:20,366 --> 00:28:23,453
Misery Chastain cannot be dead.

337
00:28:23,912 --> 00:28:27,665
Annie, in 1871, women often died
in childbirth.

338
00:28:28,208 --> 00:28:31,586
Her spirit is the important thing
and Misery's spirit is alive.

339
00:28:31,794 --> 00:28:33,463
I don't want her spirit!

340
00:28:33,755 --> 00:28:35,340
I want her!

341
00:28:35,548 --> 00:28:37,592
And you murdered her!

342
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:38,885
No.

343
00:28:39,093 --> 00:28:40,178
I didn't.

344
00:28:40,386 --> 00:28:41,554
Who did?

345
00:28:41,888 --> 00:28:42,889
No one.

346
00:28:43,097 --> 00:28:45,850
She died.
She just slipped away.

347
00:28:46,059 --> 00:28:48,394
Slipped away?!

348
00:28:48,603 --> 00:28:50,313
Slipped away?!

349
00:28:50,480 --> 00:28:53,691
She didn't just slip away!
You did it!

350
00:28:55,151 --> 00:28:59,280
You did it! You did it!

351
00:28:59,572 --> 00:29:02,075
- You murdered my Misery!
- Annie! Annie!

352
00:29:07,747 --> 00:29:09,832
I thought you were good, Paul...

353
00:29:10,458 --> 00:29:12,085
...but you're not good.

354
00:29:12,293 --> 00:29:15,505
You're just another lying,
old dirty birdie...

355
00:29:15,672 --> 00:29:19,175
...and I don't think I better be
around you for a while.

356
00:29:27,892 --> 00:29:30,728
And don't even think about
anybody coming for you.

357
00:29:30,937 --> 00:29:32,313
Not the doctors...

358
00:29:32,522 --> 00:29:33,690
...not your agent...

359
00:29:33,940 --> 00:29:35,525
...not your family...

360
00:29:35,692 --> 00:29:37,986
...because I never called them.

361
00:29:38,361 --> 00:29:40,446
Nobody knows you're here.

362
00:29:40,655 --> 00:29:43,700
And you better hope nothing happens to me.

363
00:29:44,534 --> 00:29:46,494
Because if I die...

364
00:29:46,703 --> 00:29:48,288
...you die.

365
00:32:16,436 --> 00:32:20,481
No, Ms. Sindell, there's no
point in coming up here now.

366
00:32:20,690 --> 00:32:23,359
Everything that can be done is.

367
00:32:24,277 --> 00:32:29,031
We're working close with the police,
and the FBI's been informed.

368
00:32:29,240 --> 00:32:31,451
Right. Right.

369
00:32:31,659 --> 00:32:34,245
As soon as we know anything
we'll let you know.

370
00:32:34,454 --> 00:32:35,955
No bother at all.

371
00:32:36,038 --> 00:32:39,709
Call anytime. Bye, Ms. Sindell.

372
00:32:39,876 --> 00:32:43,963
All right. Well, I sure
appreciate it. Thank you.

373
00:32:45,673 --> 00:32:50,470
According to Sheldon's credit charges,
there's nothing after Silver Creek.

374
00:32:51,220 --> 00:32:54,307
No calls about the article either.

375
00:32:56,851 --> 00:32:59,562
You poor, dear thing.

376
00:32:59,687 --> 00:33:01,939
What are you doing on the floor?

377
00:33:02,982 --> 00:33:04,734
It's all my fault.

378
00:33:05,109 --> 00:33:08,571
If I had a proper hospital bed,
this never would've happened.

379
00:33:08,779 --> 00:33:11,324
Here, let me help you back in.

380
00:33:14,160 --> 00:33:18,748
I know this hurts,
but it will only take a few seconds.

381
00:33:18,956 --> 00:33:22,418
Upsy-daisy.

382
00:33:26,964 --> 00:33:30,551
- Please. Wait. Wait.
- Oh, you're such a crybaby.

383
00:33:37,683 --> 00:33:40,269
There you go. Comfy?

384
00:33:40,728 --> 00:33:41,729
Perfect.

385
00:33:41,938 --> 00:33:43,940
Such a kidder.

386
00:33:44,232 --> 00:33:48,945
I have a big surprise for you. But
first there's something you must do.

387
00:33:49,612 --> 00:33:54,408
Do you suppose I could have a little
snack while I'm waiting for it?

388
00:33:54,617 --> 00:33:58,663
I'll get you everything you want,
but you must listen first.

389
00:33:58,955 --> 00:34:02,041
Sometimes my thinking
is a little muddy. I accept that.

390
00:34:02,917 --> 00:34:06,879
It's why I couldn't remember things
on the witness stand in Denver.

391
00:34:08,464 --> 00:34:10,508
But this time I thought clearly.

392
00:34:10,758 --> 00:34:12,301
I asked God about you.

393
00:34:12,468 --> 00:34:16,597
And God said, "I delivered him unto
you so that you may show him the way."

394
00:34:17,223 --> 00:34:18,641
Show me the way?

395
00:34:19,058 --> 00:34:20,768
Yes.

396
00:34:53,718 --> 00:34:57,013
When I mentioned a snack,
I was thinking more of a...

397
00:34:57,221 --> 00:34:59,307
...cheese and crackers kind of thing.

398
00:34:59,515 --> 00:35:02,643
Paul, this is no time for jokes.

399
00:35:02,977 --> 00:35:05,313
You must rid the world of this filth.

400
00:35:07,982 --> 00:35:09,859
You want me to burn my book?

401
00:35:10,318 --> 00:35:14,280
I know this may be difficult for you,
but it's for the best.

402
00:35:17,491 --> 00:35:20,244
It's really not difficult at all.

403
00:35:20,328 --> 00:35:23,956
My agent made dozens of copies.
There'll be an auction in New York.

404
00:35:24,206 --> 00:35:26,667
Publishing houses in New York
are reading it now.

405
00:35:26,876 --> 00:35:29,045
So if you want me to burn my book, fine.

406
00:35:29,211 --> 00:35:32,381
But you're not really
ridding the world of anything.

407
00:35:32,715 --> 00:35:34,800
Then light the match, Paul.

408
00:35:35,384 --> 00:35:37,345
It's no big deal.

409
00:35:37,553 --> 00:35:39,722
So you've indicated.

410
00:35:39,889 --> 00:35:41,015
Do it.

411
00:35:50,524 --> 00:35:52,234
This is the only copy, Paul.

412
00:35:52,401 --> 00:35:57,239
You didn't think your first book would
be taken seriously enough to copy.

413
00:35:57,448 --> 00:36:01,077
They did. You've never made copies
because you're superstitious.

414
00:36:01,327 --> 00:36:03,527
It's why you always come back
to the Silver Creek Lodge.

415
00:36:03,621 --> 00:36:06,123
You told that
to Merv Griffin 11 years ago.

416
00:36:14,465 --> 00:36:15,675
I'll tell you what.

417
00:36:15,925 --> 00:36:17,927
It doesn't ever have to be published.

418
00:36:18,135 --> 00:36:21,013
No one has to read it,
I'll just keep it for myself.

419
00:36:21,222 --> 00:36:23,808
No one will even know it exists.

420
00:36:24,642 --> 00:36:29,063
As long as it does exist,
your mind won't ever be free.

421
00:36:32,775 --> 00:36:35,277
I think you should light the match, Paul.

422
00:36:44,203 --> 00:36:46,789
Can't you see it's what God wants?

423
00:36:47,248 --> 00:36:51,627
You're so brilliant, I'd think
you'd certainly be able to see that.

424
00:36:53,838 --> 00:36:57,091
We're put on this earth
to help people, Paul.

425
00:36:57,550 --> 00:36:59,802
Like I'm trying to help you.

426
00:37:01,303 --> 00:37:05,891
Please, help me help you.

427
00:37:23,534 --> 00:37:25,536
You're doing the right thing.

428
00:37:34,670 --> 00:37:38,174
Oh, my goodness! Goodness gracious!

429
00:37:42,636 --> 00:37:46,432
Oh, goodness! Heavens to Betsy!

430
00:37:46,682 --> 00:37:48,642
Oh, my goodness! Oh, my goodness!

431
00:37:51,353 --> 00:37:55,357
Heavens to Betsy! Oh, goodness!

432
00:38:13,793 --> 00:38:16,295
Well, isn't that an oogy mess?

433
00:38:37,942 --> 00:38:40,861
That's the Steadman place down there.

434
00:38:41,278 --> 00:38:43,823
And that's the Wilkes farm straight ahead.

435
00:38:47,159 --> 00:38:49,703
That's no '65 Mustang.

436
00:38:51,288 --> 00:38:54,875
There's nothing else out this way.
Let's circle back.

437
00:39:07,555 --> 00:39:11,141
I do believe the winters are getting
shorter every year.

438
00:39:11,392 --> 00:39:14,812
People say it has something to do
with the ozone layer.

439
00:39:15,229 --> 00:39:16,313
What do you think?

440
00:39:17,815 --> 00:39:19,567
I don't know.

441
00:39:20,442 --> 00:39:22,611
Yeah, well, it's a theory.

442
00:39:30,953 --> 00:39:32,788
Here's your Novril.

443
00:40:11,201 --> 00:40:14,121
<i>We're back. Now, remind us
who the audience chose.</i>

444
00:40:14,330 --> 00:40:16,332
<i>- They chose Kevin.
- They chose Kevin.</i>

445
00:40:16,540 --> 00:40:18,459
<i>In fact, say hello to Kevin Andrews.</i>

446
00:40:18,667 --> 00:40:19,710
<i>Hi, Kevin.</i>

447
00:40:19,919 --> 00:40:20,878
<i>How you doing, Chuck?</i>

448
00:40:21,086 --> 00:40:25,090
<i>Make yourself at home and Sheri
will tell us about the date.</i>

449
00:40:26,216 --> 00:40:29,011
<i>First of all, I picked out
a very classy restaurant.</i>

450
00:40:29,178 --> 00:40:33,390
<i>It was so classy, and he shows up
without no tie...</i>

451
00:41:32,408 --> 00:41:34,410
See, isn't this nice?

452
00:41:34,576 --> 00:41:37,913
Great, I always wanted to visit the
other side of the room.

453
00:41:38,122 --> 00:41:40,708
Look what I got for you.

454
00:41:42,251 --> 00:41:46,422
An electric razor so you can
shave yourself now.

455
00:41:49,842 --> 00:41:52,928
For this surprise
I'd have burned all my books.

456
00:41:53,137 --> 00:41:56,557
Now, don't poke fun.

457
00:41:57,099 --> 00:42:01,770
This is a big day for you, Paul.
Sit tight and I'll set everything up.

458
00:42:03,063 --> 00:42:04,314
Set what up?

459
00:42:04,523 --> 00:42:06,108
That's the big surprise.

460
00:42:07,109 --> 00:42:08,736
Your new studio.

461
00:42:09,778 --> 00:42:13,115
After all, writers do need
a place to work.

462
00:42:13,407 --> 00:42:16,326
Work? You mean, write?

463
00:42:17,911 --> 00:42:19,705
What in the world would I write?

464
00:42:20,289 --> 00:42:24,209
Oh, but Paul, I don't think. I know.

465
00:42:24,460 --> 00:42:29,298
You've burned that nasty manuscript.
Now you can do what you're great at.

466
00:42:29,882 --> 00:42:33,761
You're gonna write a new novel.
Your greatest achievement ever.

467
00:42:33,969 --> 00:42:36,138
Misery's return.

468
00:42:36,805 --> 00:42:38,766
Misery's return?

469
00:42:39,183 --> 00:42:43,979
You didn't mean it when you killed
her, and now you'll make it right.

470
00:42:45,355 --> 00:42:47,274
It'll be a book in my honor...

471
00:42:47,691 --> 00:42:50,652
...for saving your life
and nursing you back to health.

472
00:42:51,195 --> 00:42:55,574
Oh, Paul, you're gonna make me
the envy of the whole world.

473
00:42:56,075 --> 00:42:58,827
You just expect me to whip something off?

474
00:42:59,328 --> 00:43:02,372
I expect nothing less
than your masterpiece.

475
00:43:04,374 --> 00:43:09,588
You understand that this is not
the ordinary way books get written.

476
00:43:09,797 --> 00:43:13,258
Some people might consider this
an oddball situation.

477
00:43:13,467 --> 00:43:15,844
I have total confidence
in your brilliance.

478
00:43:16,011 --> 00:43:19,014
Besides, the view will inspire you.

479
00:43:19,181 --> 00:43:22,684
You just inhale that.
I'll be right back.

480
00:43:34,196 --> 00:43:36,365
I guess neighbors don't bother you?

481
00:43:36,532 --> 00:43:37,658
Don't you worry...

482
00:43:37,866 --> 00:43:41,870
...you'll have total solitude
so you can concentrate on your work.

483
00:43:42,037 --> 00:43:43,497
Great.

484
00:43:44,957 --> 00:43:47,960
I got you this expensive paper to type on.

485
00:43:48,168 --> 00:43:52,422
And I got a good deal on this clunker
on account of it's missing an "N."

486
00:43:52,798 --> 00:43:57,511
{\an8}I told the lady "N" was one of the
letters in my favorite writer's name.

487
00:44:00,389 --> 00:44:04,643
It's two of the letters in my
favorite nurse's name: Annie.

488
00:44:04,977 --> 00:44:08,730
You fooler. Did I do good?

489
00:44:09,064 --> 00:44:10,190
You did great.

490
00:44:13,944 --> 00:44:17,322
There is just one little thing.

491
00:44:19,408 --> 00:44:23,912
I can't work on this paper. See, it's
Corrasable Bond and it smudges.

492
00:44:24,830 --> 00:44:27,040
I thought maybe if you...

493
00:44:27,749 --> 00:44:31,712
...went back into town, you could
get some white long-grained mimeo.

494
00:44:33,422 --> 00:44:37,342
But mine cost the most,
so I don't see how it can smudge.

495
00:44:38,343 --> 00:44:39,970
Come here, I'll show you.

496
00:44:59,323 --> 00:45:01,283
It does smudge after all.

497
00:45:01,992 --> 00:45:04,077
Isn't that fascinating?

498
00:45:04,411 --> 00:45:06,371
I thought you'd be interested.

499
00:45:06,705 --> 00:45:08,957
I'd like you to be in on
everything, Annie.

500
00:45:09,124 --> 00:45:12,753
Not just the finished book,
but how it's written.

501
00:45:13,879 --> 00:45:16,089
Thank you for thinking of me.

502
00:45:20,302 --> 00:45:22,804
Anything else I can get while I'm in town?

503
00:45:23,513 --> 00:45:26,141
Any other crucial requirements
I can satisfy?

504
00:45:26,808 --> 00:45:28,727
Would you like a tiny tape recorder?

505
00:45:29,228 --> 00:45:31,480
Or how about handmade writing slippers?

506
00:45:32,147 --> 00:45:34,900
Just the paper will be fine.

507
00:45:35,192 --> 00:45:38,654
Are you sure? If you want,
I'll bring back the whole store.

508
00:45:39,863 --> 00:45:42,908
Annie, what's the matter?

509
00:45:42,991 --> 00:45:46,912
I'll tell you what's the matter!
I go out of my way for you!

510
00:45:47,120 --> 00:45:48,914
I do everything to make you happy!

511
00:45:49,122 --> 00:45:51,667
I feed you! I clean you!
I dress you!

512
00:45:51,875 --> 00:45:56,505
And what thanks do I get?!
"You bought the wrong paper, Annie!"

513
00:45:57,214 --> 00:46:02,010
I'll get your paper, but you better
show me more appreciation, Mr. Man.

514
00:47:31,850 --> 00:47:33,268
Shit!

515
00:47:55,040 --> 00:47:58,460
Come on, you've written about this,
now do it.

516
00:48:06,134 --> 00:48:07,803
What do you know? It works.

517
00:48:39,835 --> 00:48:41,837
What a surprise.

518
00:49:21,710 --> 00:49:23,962
You crazy bitch.

519
00:54:50,288 --> 00:54:52,957
Paul, I've got your paper.

520
00:54:53,208 --> 00:54:56,169
I hope it's enough.
Three reams of long-grained mimeo.

521
00:54:57,378 --> 00:54:59,672
Just the kind you asked for.

522
00:55:00,715 --> 00:55:02,133
Paul.

523
00:55:02,675 --> 00:55:05,094
You're dripping with perspiration.

524
00:55:05,637 --> 00:55:08,515
Your color is very hectic.
What've you been doing?

525
00:55:08,973 --> 00:55:11,392
You know damn well what I've been doing.

526
00:55:11,851 --> 00:55:15,104
I've been sitting here suffering.
I need my pills.

527
00:55:16,064 --> 00:55:17,357
Poor dear.

528
00:55:17,565 --> 00:55:19,901
Let's get you in bed, and I'll get them.

529
00:55:20,109 --> 00:55:21,528
I want my pills now!

530
00:55:21,903 --> 00:55:24,239
- It'll only take a second.
- No!

531
00:55:25,240 --> 00:55:28,952
I want my pain to go away, Annie.

532
00:55:29,577 --> 00:55:32,580
Please, make it go away.

533
00:55:33,540 --> 00:55:35,208
Please, Annie.

534
00:55:36,376 --> 00:55:37,919
Please.

535
00:55:41,005 --> 00:55:44,300
It just breaks my heart
to see you like this.

536
00:55:54,227 --> 00:55:56,271
I've done a lot of thinking on the drive.

537
00:55:56,521 --> 00:55:58,231
Here you go.

538
00:55:58,773 --> 00:56:00,441
And I'm absolutely certain.

539
00:56:00,650 --> 00:56:04,946
The main reason I've never been
more popular is because of my temper.

540
00:56:05,113 --> 00:56:07,574
You must be so mad at me.

541
00:56:07,782 --> 00:56:09,492
The truth, now.

542
00:56:10,451 --> 00:56:11,369
Well...

543
00:56:12,287 --> 00:56:15,498
Who doesn't let off a little steam
every once in a while?

544
00:56:16,541 --> 00:56:19,544
My genius needs his rest before he writes.

545
00:56:25,091 --> 00:56:26,968
Footsies up.

546
00:56:28,011 --> 00:56:29,804
There you go.

547
00:56:42,650 --> 00:56:43,818
Here.

548
00:56:44,652 --> 00:56:46,487
In case you think of any ideas.

549
00:56:47,864 --> 00:56:49,991
I wouldn't expect too much.

550
00:56:50,867 --> 00:56:54,037
Don't be silly. You'll be brilliant.

551
00:56:54,245 --> 00:56:56,915
Think of me as your inspiration.

552
00:57:01,294 --> 00:57:03,671
I have faith in you, my darling.

553
00:57:04,213 --> 00:57:05,548
Catch this.

554
00:57:49,842 --> 00:57:53,346
The presumption must now be
that Paul Sheldon is dead.

555
00:57:54,263 --> 00:57:57,183
We know he somehow managed
to crawl outside his car...

556
00:57:57,392 --> 00:58:01,479
...but we haven't found his body
in the vicinity of the accident.

557
00:58:01,688 --> 00:58:05,733
Also, had anyone found him,
they would've taken him to a hospital.

558
00:58:06,234 --> 00:58:09,862
Undoubtedly, he is buried
somewhere out there in the snow.

559
00:58:10,071 --> 00:58:11,948
We'll find him after the thaw.

560
00:58:12,156 --> 00:58:14,117
Unless the animals get to him first...

561
00:58:14,325 --> 00:58:16,285
...which is a distinct possibility.

562
00:58:17,203 --> 00:58:21,249
That was a statement from Colorado
Police Chief, Sherman Douglas.

563
00:58:21,416 --> 00:58:22,417
We will update you--

564
00:58:32,427 --> 00:58:34,595
You don't think he's dead, do you?

565
00:58:34,762 --> 00:58:38,016
Well, he might well be,
but not the way they say.

566
00:58:38,433 --> 00:58:41,019
He never crawled out
of that car by himself.

567
00:58:41,227 --> 00:58:43,521
You can see the dents on the door there.

568
00:58:43,813 --> 00:58:45,606
Someone pulled him out.

569
01:00:38,469 --> 01:00:40,555
I'm sorry, Paul. This is all wrong.

570
01:00:41,055 --> 01:00:43,391
- What?
- You'll have to do it over again.

571
01:00:43,808 --> 01:00:46,144
It's not worthy of you.
Throw it all out.

572
01:00:46,352 --> 01:00:50,273
Except naming the gravedigger
after me. You can leave that in.

573
01:00:52,233 --> 01:00:56,779
I really value your criticism, but
maybe you're being a bit hasty here.

574
01:00:56,988 --> 01:00:59,240
What you've written just isn't fair.

575
01:00:59,699 --> 01:01:01,909
- Not fair?
- That's right.

576
01:01:02,076 --> 01:01:04,745
Growing up in Bakersfield,
my favorite thing...

577
01:01:04,954 --> 01:01:07,999
...was to go to the movies on
Saturdays for chapter plays.

578
01:01:08,207 --> 01:01:11,085
- Cliffhangers.
- I know that, Mr. Man!

579
01:01:11,252 --> 01:01:14,839
They also call them serials.
I'm not stupid, you know!

580
01:01:17,925 --> 01:01:22,054
Anyway, my favorite was Rocket Man.
And once it was a no-brakes chapter.

581
01:01:22,263 --> 01:01:24,599
The bad guys put him
in a car on a mountain...

582
01:01:24,765 --> 01:01:28,436
...knocked him out, welded the doors,
and started him to his death.

583
01:01:28,686 --> 01:01:31,063
He woke up, tried to steer,
tried to get out.

584
01:01:31,272 --> 01:01:35,026
But the car went off a cliff before
he escaped and crashed and burned!

585
01:01:35,234 --> 01:01:39,113
I was so upset and excited!
Next week, I was first in line.

586
01:01:39,322 --> 01:01:41,157
It starts with last week's ending.

587
01:01:41,365 --> 01:01:45,411
There was Rocket Man, trying
to get out and here comes the cliff.

588
01:01:45,620 --> 01:01:48,706
Just before the car went
off the cliff, he jumped free!

589
01:01:48,915 --> 01:01:50,791
And all the kids cheered!

590
01:01:51,459 --> 01:01:52,752
But I didn't cheer.

591
01:01:52,960 --> 01:01:55,087
I stood right up and started shouting:

592
01:01:55,296 --> 01:01:59,008
"This isn't what happened last week!
Have you all got amnesia?

593
01:01:59,217 --> 01:02:01,969
They just cheated us!
This isn't fair!

594
01:02:02,178 --> 01:02:06,515
He didn't get out
of the cock-a-doodie car!"

595
01:02:12,980 --> 01:02:16,067
They always cheated like that
in cliff-- Chapter plays.

596
01:02:16,275 --> 01:02:17,944
But not you.

597
01:02:18,778 --> 01:02:20,529
Not with my Misery.

598
01:02:20,905 --> 01:02:25,159
Ian rode for Dr. Cleary at the end
of the last book, but his horse fell.

599
01:02:25,368 --> 01:02:29,038
Ian got hurt and lay in the ditch.
He never reached the doctor.

600
01:02:29,247 --> 01:02:33,167
So there couldn't have been
a blood transfusion to save her.

601
01:02:33,626 --> 01:02:36,045
Misery was buried
in the ground at the end...

602
01:02:36,254 --> 01:02:38,172
...so you'll have to start there.

603
01:03:18,462 --> 01:03:19,880
Is it fair?

604
01:03:20,381 --> 01:03:21,590
Should I continue?

605
01:03:22,383 --> 01:03:24,218
You better.

606
01:03:24,343 --> 01:03:25,761
Oh, Paul!

607
01:03:26,262 --> 01:03:28,931
When Ian realized
they'd buried Misery alive...

608
01:03:29,140 --> 01:03:32,059
...because the bee sting had
put her in that temporary coma.

609
01:03:32,310 --> 01:03:34,937
When Gravedigger Wilkes
recalled how 30 years ago...

610
01:03:35,146 --> 01:03:37,732
...the same thing had happened
to Lady Evelyn-Hyde!

611
01:03:37,940 --> 01:03:42,403
Then Dr. Cleary deduced Misery must be
Lady Evelyn-Hyde's lost daughter...

612
01:03:42,570 --> 01:03:46,407
...because of the rarity of deadly
bee stings. My heart just leapt!

613
01:03:46,615 --> 01:03:50,870
I've known from the start that Misery
was born of nobility, and I was right!

614
01:03:51,078 --> 01:03:52,079
Yeah, yeah.

615
01:03:52,246 --> 01:03:56,459
Paul, can I read each chapter when
you finish? I can fill in the "N" s.

616
01:03:57,460 --> 01:04:01,339
Will she be herself after Ian's
dug her out, or will she have amnesia?

617
01:04:01,547 --> 01:04:02,715
Have to wait.

618
01:04:02,923 --> 01:04:05,718
Will she still love him
with that special, perfect love?

619
01:04:05,926 --> 01:04:07,219
You'll have to wait.

620
01:04:07,428 --> 01:04:08,679
Not even a hint?

621
01:04:11,307 --> 01:04:14,226
Misery's alive! Misery's alive!

622
01:04:14,435 --> 01:04:19,148
Oh, it's so romantic! Oh, this whole
house will be filled with romance!

623
01:04:19,357 --> 01:04:22,151
I'm gonna put on my Liberace records!

624
01:04:26,113 --> 01:04:28,282
You do like Liberace, don't you?

625
01:04:29,075 --> 01:04:32,828
Whenever he played Radio City,
who do you think was in the front row?

626
01:04:33,037 --> 01:04:35,915
I'll play my records all day
to inspire you.

627
01:04:36,123 --> 01:04:37,792
He's my all-time favorite.

628
01:04:42,338 --> 01:04:44,715
Would you have dinner with me tonight?

629
01:04:44,924 --> 01:04:46,926
To celebrate Misery's return.

630
01:04:49,970 --> 01:04:52,014
I couldn't have done it without you.

631
01:04:54,600 --> 01:04:56,268
Oh, Paul.

632
01:04:57,937 --> 01:04:59,814
It would be an honor.

633
01:05:06,946 --> 01:05:08,823
No, he's not here.

634
01:05:09,031 --> 01:05:12,118
I don't know where he is.
He never tells me anything.

635
01:05:12,326 --> 01:05:15,287
He's probably out having
an affair somewhere.

636
01:05:15,746 --> 01:05:18,332
Wait a minute. He's coming in now.

637
01:05:18,499 --> 01:05:22,336
It's Jim Taylor. He wants to know
who you're having an affair with.

638
01:05:23,587 --> 01:05:25,673
Hello, Jim. What's doing?

639
01:05:28,092 --> 01:05:30,719
{\an8}Jim, we've been through this before.

640
01:05:30,928 --> 01:05:33,347
{\an8}If you have benches
in front of your store...

641
01:05:33,556 --> 01:05:35,933
{\an8}...people are gonna want
to sit on them.

642
01:05:37,017 --> 01:05:38,352
{\an8}I don't like him either...

643
01:05:38,561 --> 01:05:41,564
{\an8}...but I'm not coming over there
to tell him to move.

644
01:05:42,565 --> 01:05:45,401
Give my best to Denise. Bye.

645
01:05:46,193 --> 01:05:49,572
Well, whoever she is,
she sure likes to read a lot.

646
01:05:52,533 --> 01:05:56,036
I'm flattered that you think
I've got that much energy.

647
01:05:57,079 --> 01:05:59,415
I figured if I can't find Paul Sheldon...

648
01:05:59,623 --> 01:06:02,460
...at least I can find out
what he wrote about.

649
01:06:02,751 --> 01:06:04,211
What do you expect to find?

650
01:06:04,420 --> 01:06:08,883
A story about a guy who drove his car
off a cliff in a snowstorm?

651
01:06:10,259 --> 01:06:12,636
You see, it's just that kind of sarcasm...

652
01:06:12,845 --> 01:06:15,681
...that's given
our marriage real spice.

653
01:06:29,487 --> 01:06:30,571
I hope you like it.

654
01:06:30,946 --> 01:06:32,490
It looks wonderful.

655
01:06:33,365 --> 01:06:34,366
So do you.

656
01:07:03,938 --> 01:07:07,024
I've never had meat loaf this good.
What do you do to it?

657
01:07:07,441 --> 01:07:10,444
My secret is I only use
fresh tomatoes, never canned.

658
01:07:10,653 --> 01:07:14,448
To give it that little extra zip,
I mix in Spam with the ground beef.

659
01:07:18,285 --> 01:07:20,621
Can't get this
in a restaurant in New York.

660
01:07:28,629 --> 01:07:29,713
Let's have a toast.

661
01:07:29,922 --> 01:07:30,923
A toast?

662
01:07:31,131 --> 01:07:33,467
Yes. To Misery.

663
01:07:33,676 --> 01:07:35,302
Let me pour you some wine.

664
01:07:40,057 --> 01:07:41,308
No.

665
01:07:53,070 --> 01:07:54,071
To Misery.

666
01:07:58,117 --> 01:07:59,118
Wait.

667
01:08:00,077 --> 01:08:02,329
Let's do this right.
Do you have any candles?

668
01:08:05,291 --> 01:08:08,168
I don't know. I-- I think so.

669
01:08:08,711 --> 01:08:10,004
I'll go look.

670
01:08:17,803 --> 01:08:20,973
Did you study decorating
or do you just have a flair?

671
01:08:21,181 --> 01:08:23,642
Oh, you!

672
01:08:23,851 --> 01:08:26,979
I just picked things up over the years.

673
01:08:27,187 --> 01:08:29,273
Well, it certainly says "you."

674
01:08:29,481 --> 01:08:31,358
You really think so?

675
01:08:31,525 --> 01:08:33,360
Absolutely.

676
01:08:33,944 --> 01:08:35,904
If you can't find any, it's okay.

677
01:08:36,113 --> 01:08:37,698
I just thought it'd be nice.

678
01:08:38,782 --> 01:08:39,783
Are you kidding?

679
01:08:39,992 --> 01:08:42,036
If anyone had told me I'd be having...

680
01:08:42,202 --> 01:08:45,581
...a candle-lit dinner
with Paul Sheldon in my own house...

681
01:08:45,789 --> 01:08:49,376
...I would've checked both legs
to see which one was being pulled.

682
01:08:51,962 --> 01:08:53,130
Will this do?

683
01:08:53,756 --> 01:08:55,215
It's perfect.

684
01:09:00,763 --> 01:09:02,222
To Misery...

685
01:09:02,389 --> 01:09:06,060
...and to Annie Wilkes,
who brought her back to life.

686
01:09:06,268 --> 01:09:10,564
Oh, Paul, I get goosebumps
every time I think about it.

687
01:09:12,816 --> 01:09:14,943
Oh, my God. What have I done?

688
01:09:15,152 --> 01:09:16,737
I'm so sorry, Paul.

689
01:09:17,279 --> 01:09:19,907
I ruined your beautiful toast.

690
01:09:22,409 --> 01:09:24,244
Will you ever forgive me?

691
01:09:24,953 --> 01:09:26,789
Here, let me pour another one.

692
01:09:33,379 --> 01:09:35,339
Can we pretend this never happened?

693
01:09:40,094 --> 01:09:41,595
To Misery.

694
01:09:42,179 --> 01:09:43,639
To Misery.

695
01:10:28,100 --> 01:10:31,937
Paul, this is positively the best
Misery you've ever written.

696
01:11:41,215 --> 01:11:42,883
Here's your pills.

697
01:11:44,635 --> 01:11:45,636
Annie?

698
01:11:49,389 --> 01:11:50,933
Annie, what is it?

699
01:11:52,351 --> 01:11:53,769
The rain.

700
01:11:55,646 --> 01:11:58,065
Sometimes it gives me the blues.

701
01:12:01,443 --> 01:12:03,570
When you first came here...

702
01:12:04,613 --> 01:12:07,741
...I only loved the writer part
of Paul Sheldon.

703
01:12:09,743 --> 01:12:12,746
Now I know I love the rest of him too.

704
01:12:19,169 --> 01:12:21,213
I know you don't love me.

705
01:12:22,589 --> 01:12:24,258
Don't say you do.

706
01:12:25,926 --> 01:12:27,386
You're a beautiful...

707
01:12:27,594 --> 01:12:28,929
...brilliant...

708
01:12:29,096 --> 01:12:30,514
...famous man of the world...

709
01:12:31,265 --> 01:12:32,432
...and I'm...

710
01:12:33,976 --> 01:12:36,103
...not a movie-star type.

711
01:12:42,276 --> 01:12:45,279
You'll never know the fear
of losing someone like you...

712
01:12:45,445 --> 01:12:47,447
...if you're someone like me.

713
01:12:48,740 --> 01:12:50,701
Why would you lose me?

714
01:12:54,371 --> 01:12:56,540
The book's almost finished.

715
01:12:58,834 --> 01:13:00,961
Your legs are getting better.

716
01:13:02,462 --> 01:13:04,715
Soon, you'll be wanting to leave.

717
01:13:05,549 --> 01:13:07,217
Why would I leave?

718
01:13:07,426 --> 01:13:08,969
I like it here.

719
01:13:09,636 --> 01:13:11,722
That's very kind of you.

720
01:13:12,556 --> 01:13:15,142
But I'll bet it's not altogether true.

721
01:13:32,451 --> 01:13:34,494
I have this gun.

722
01:13:38,665 --> 01:13:41,168
Sometimes I think about using it.

723
01:13:47,674 --> 01:13:49,426
I better go now.

724
01:13:52,346 --> 01:13:54,389
I might put bullets in it.

725
01:14:42,729 --> 01:14:45,649
"There is a justice higher
than that of man...

726
01:14:45,857 --> 01:14:48,110
...I will be judged by Him."

727
01:14:48,318 --> 01:14:49,319
What?

728
01:14:49,528 --> 01:14:51,905
They're hauling Misery into court.

729
01:14:53,156 --> 01:14:54,700
That's nice.

730
01:15:02,749 --> 01:15:04,876
"There is a justice...

731
01:15:05,085 --> 01:15:07,879
...higher than that of man...

732
01:15:08,755 --> 01:15:12,259
...I will be judged...

733
01:15:12,467 --> 01:15:13,969
...by Him."

734
01:19:16,169 --> 01:19:20,215
<i>Welcome to Love Connection!</i>

735
01:19:20,423 --> 01:19:24,135
<i>Where old-fashioned romance
meets modern-day technology.</i>

736
01:19:25,929 --> 01:19:30,016
<i>Where you hear all
the intimate details of the date.</i>

737
01:19:37,148 --> 01:19:39,067
See you in the morning.

738
01:20:38,126 --> 01:20:39,544
Paul.

739
01:20:46,343 --> 01:20:47,969
I know you've been out.

740
01:20:53,099 --> 01:20:55,977
- What?
- You've been out of your room.

741
01:20:57,729 --> 01:20:59,064
No, I haven't.

742
01:20:59,564 --> 01:21:00,940
Paul.

743
01:21:01,232 --> 01:21:05,445
My little ceramic penguin
in the study always faces due south.

744
01:21:07,280 --> 01:21:10,408
I don't know what you're talking about.

745
01:21:11,117 --> 01:21:13,078
Ceramic penguin?

746
01:21:14,204 --> 01:21:16,373
Is this what you're looking for?

747
01:21:18,792 --> 01:21:20,585
I know you've been out twice.

748
01:21:21,419 --> 01:21:25,090
At first, I couldn't figure out
how you did it, but last night...

749
01:21:25,632 --> 01:21:27,300
...I found your key.

750
01:21:30,637 --> 01:21:33,306
I know I left my scrapbook out.

751
01:21:33,473 --> 01:21:36,101
I can imagine what you
might be thinking of me.

752
01:21:36,309 --> 01:21:37,894
But you see, it's all okay.

753
01:21:38,812 --> 01:21:41,022
Last night, it came so clear.

754
01:21:41,231 --> 01:21:43,316
I realized you just need more time.

755
01:21:43,483 --> 01:21:46,653
Eventually, you'll come to accept
the idea of being here.

756
01:21:47,987 --> 01:21:51,991
Paul, do you know about the early days
at the Kimberly Diamond Mines?

757
01:21:52,200 --> 01:21:55,620
Do you know what they did to
the workers who stole diamonds?

758
01:21:55,912 --> 01:21:58,123
Don't worry, they didn't kill them.

759
01:21:58,373 --> 01:22:01,960
That'd be like junking a Mercedes
because it had a broken spring.

760
01:22:02,168 --> 01:22:05,463
If they caught them, they had to make
sure they could still work.

761
01:22:05,672 --> 01:22:08,299
They also had to make sure
they couldn't run away.

762
01:22:08,800 --> 01:22:11,261
The operation was called "hobbling."

763
01:22:21,187 --> 01:22:22,355
Annie.

764
01:22:23,356 --> 01:22:27,193
Whatever you're thinking about doing,
please don't do it.

765
01:22:31,906 --> 01:22:33,199
Annie, for God--

766
01:22:33,366 --> 01:22:34,868
Shh, darling.

767
01:22:35,034 --> 01:22:36,035
Trust me.

768
01:22:36,327 --> 01:22:38,746
- God's sake!
- It's for the best.

769
01:22:38,955 --> 01:22:40,123
Please!

770
01:22:42,917 --> 01:22:44,544
Almost done.

771
01:22:44,752 --> 01:22:46,421
Just one more.

772
01:22:55,346 --> 01:22:56,973
God, I love you.

773
01:23:27,337 --> 01:23:29,714
You cock-a-doodie!

774
01:23:43,269 --> 01:23:45,438
- Sit on this!
- You poop!

775
01:24:01,329 --> 01:24:02,997
Just leave it, all right?

776
01:24:03,206 --> 01:24:05,250
Oh, I like that tone.

777
01:24:05,458 --> 01:24:08,628
How many times I have to tell you?
I have a system here.

778
01:24:09,212 --> 01:24:11,464
- Where the hell is that thing?
- What thing?

779
01:24:11,673 --> 01:24:13,091
The thing!

780
01:24:14,217 --> 01:24:16,302
Here it is. Right where it should be.

781
01:24:16,511 --> 01:24:17,595
What is it?

782
01:24:18,304 --> 01:24:20,640
I'm not sure. Maybe nothing.

783
01:24:20,848 --> 01:24:22,642
Well, I'm glad you found it.

784
01:24:22,850 --> 01:24:25,019
There's that spice again.

785
01:25:40,762 --> 01:25:42,013
Come on, Mizzy.

786
01:25:42,764 --> 01:25:43,973
Come on.

787
01:25:44,515 --> 01:25:46,100
Hi, pumpkin!

788
01:25:49,145 --> 01:25:50,980
Such a kidder.

789
01:25:51,230 --> 01:25:53,149
Come on, Misery.

790
01:25:55,610 --> 01:25:56,986
Come on, Mizzy.

791
01:26:02,742 --> 01:26:03,951
Hey, Pete.

792
01:26:04,619 --> 01:26:05,745
Buster.

793
01:26:05,953 --> 01:26:07,914
Answer me a couple of things.

794
01:26:08,081 --> 01:26:09,582
If I can.

795
01:26:09,749 --> 01:26:12,085
Do you have any new Paul Sheldon books?

796
01:26:12,251 --> 01:26:15,838
Well, we had a batch.
Sold them all out in three days.

797
01:26:16,047 --> 01:26:19,759
Would you happen to know
if Ms. Wilkes bought one of them?

798
01:26:20,468 --> 01:26:22,011
Are you kidding?

799
01:26:22,220 --> 01:26:26,724
Every time he writes a new book,
she has me set aside the first copy.

800
01:26:28,101 --> 01:26:31,062
Has she been buying anything odd lately?

801
01:26:31,270 --> 01:26:32,730
Ms. Wilkes?

802
01:26:33,606 --> 01:26:35,441
Same old stuff.

803
01:26:35,775 --> 01:26:38,319
Lest you call paper odd.

804
01:26:38,611 --> 01:26:39,612
Newspaper?

805
01:26:39,946 --> 01:26:42,740
No. The typing kind.

806
01:26:42,949 --> 01:26:46,202
Oh, that kind.
Nothing odd about that.

807
01:26:46,452 --> 01:26:47,870
Ms. Wilkes done something?

808
01:26:48,287 --> 01:26:49,914
Not a thing.

809
01:27:50,683 --> 01:27:52,185
I'll never understand you.

810
01:27:52,351 --> 01:27:56,230
I cook your meals, I tend to you
practically 24 hours a day...

811
01:27:56,439 --> 01:27:58,399
...and you continue to fight me.

812
01:27:58,608 --> 01:28:01,110
When are we going to develop
a sense of trust?

813
01:28:30,348 --> 01:28:31,724
Oh, my.

814
01:28:32,016 --> 01:28:36,062
I didn't mean to startle you, but you
didn't give me a chance to knock.

815
01:28:36,395 --> 01:28:40,233
You can tell from my reaction, I'm not
all that used to visitors out here.

816
01:28:40,441 --> 01:28:41,734
What can I do for you?

817
01:28:41,943 --> 01:28:45,822
I was wondering, do you happen
to know anything about Paul Sheldon?

818
01:28:46,781 --> 01:28:51,410
- What do you want to know?
- Anything you could say might help.

819
01:28:52,620 --> 01:28:55,414
He was born in Worcester,
Massachusetts 45 years ago...

820
01:28:55,581 --> 01:28:58,918
...the only child of Franklin and
Helene Sheldon, majored in history.

821
01:28:59,126 --> 01:29:02,046
That isn't the kind
of information I'm after.

822
01:29:02,255 --> 01:29:04,882
You see, he's been missing
for quite some time--

823
01:29:05,091 --> 01:29:07,927
I know. It's so upsetting.
I'm his number one fan.

824
01:29:08,094 --> 01:29:10,596
I've got all his books,
every sentence he ever put down.

825
01:29:10,805 --> 01:29:13,558
I'm so proud of my Paul Sheldon
collection.

826
01:29:15,601 --> 01:29:19,564
Well, here I am, prattling on
and my manners have just flown away.

827
01:29:19,772 --> 01:29:22,024
I haven't invited you in. Please.

828
01:29:22,233 --> 01:29:23,234
Thank you.

829
01:29:24,527 --> 01:29:27,363
You must know
all about that horrible accident.

830
01:29:27,947 --> 01:29:31,075
- Mind if I take a look around?
- Of course not.

831
01:29:32,201 --> 01:29:34,620
That accident almost killed me too.

832
01:29:34,787 --> 01:29:36,622
I prayed when I heard the news.

833
01:29:36,789 --> 01:29:40,126
I got down on my knees and I begged
for it not to be true.

834
01:29:40,293 --> 01:29:44,380
You're gonna laugh at what I'm about
to say, but go ahead, I don't care.

835
01:29:45,298 --> 01:29:49,051
When I was praying,
God told me to get ready.

836
01:29:49,552 --> 01:29:52,805
- Get ready for what?
- To be his replacement.

837
01:29:53,139 --> 01:29:55,850
He gave so much pleasure
to so many people.

838
01:29:56,058 --> 01:30:00,938
There's a shortage of pleasure these
days, in case you hadn't noticed.

839
01:30:01,147 --> 01:30:03,733
God told me, since I was
his number one fan...

840
01:30:03,941 --> 01:30:07,320
...that I should make up new stories
as if I was Paul Sheldon.

841
01:30:07,528 --> 01:30:11,657
So I went to town, and I bought
a typewriter and paper to type on.

842
01:30:11,866 --> 01:30:14,327
The same kind Paul Sheldon used.

843
01:30:14,493 --> 01:30:17,163
I turned the guest bedroom
into a writing studio.

844
01:30:17,330 --> 01:30:19,582
- Would you like to see it?
- Sure.

845
01:30:19,790 --> 01:30:21,459
It's right this way.

846
01:30:31,135 --> 01:30:34,096
I know how he wrote,
the kinds of words he used...

847
01:30:34,305 --> 01:30:36,515
...the wonderful stories he told.

848
01:30:36,682 --> 01:30:39,936
I've spent the last four weeks
trying to write like him...

849
01:30:40,144 --> 01:30:41,938
...but I can't do it right.

850
01:30:42,146 --> 01:30:47,026
I try and I try and I know all
the words, but it's just not the same.

851
01:30:47,193 --> 01:30:49,362
Maybe it takes time to get the hang of it.

852
01:30:51,030 --> 01:30:54,659
I could give you 200 pages,
and you could tell me what you think.

853
01:30:54,867 --> 01:30:58,454
- I'm not much of a critic.
- Well, I just thought...

854
01:30:59,538 --> 01:31:02,041
Look at me. You'd think
I'd never had a guest.

855
01:31:02,249 --> 01:31:04,794
- Would you like a hot cup of cocoa?
- No, I--

856
01:31:05,002 --> 01:31:08,881
It's no trouble.
There's some already made.

857
01:31:15,513 --> 01:31:19,183
Must get lonely, living out here
all by yourself.

858
01:31:20,726 --> 01:31:25,606
If you can't enjoy your own company,
you're not fit company for anyone.

859
01:31:25,815 --> 01:31:27,900
Well, you've got a point there.

860
01:32:35,301 --> 01:32:37,970
- Here you are.
- Thanks, Ms. Wilkes...

861
01:32:38,137 --> 01:32:41,098
...but I don't want to take up
any more of your time.

862
01:32:42,391 --> 01:32:44,185
I best be going.

863
01:32:44,393 --> 01:32:47,480
But you didn't even taste your cocoa.

864
01:32:47,688 --> 01:32:51,817
I'm sure it's wonderful,
but I should be getting back.

865
01:32:57,156 --> 01:33:00,743
If you wouldn't mind, perhaps I
could pay you another visit some time.

866
01:33:00,951 --> 01:33:03,496
I'd be delighted.
Now that you know the way.

867
01:33:22,223 --> 01:33:23,432
Ms. Wilkes?

868
01:33:25,101 --> 01:33:27,186
Ms. Wilkes, are you all right?

869
01:33:28,145 --> 01:33:29,188
Here!

870
01:33:30,064 --> 01:33:31,774
Here! I'm down here!

871
01:33:32,858 --> 01:33:34,360
I'm down here!

872
01:33:37,655 --> 01:33:38,906
Mr. Sheldon?

873
01:33:49,750 --> 01:33:51,585
Don't feel bad, Paul.

874
01:33:52,378 --> 01:33:55,172
It was bound to happen sooner or later.

875
01:33:55,923 --> 01:33:57,299
It's a sign.

876
01:33:59,426 --> 01:34:03,430
You see, I've known for some time
why I was chosen to save you.

877
01:34:04,098 --> 01:34:06,851
You and I were meant
to be together forever.

878
01:34:07,560 --> 01:34:09,937
But now our time in this world must end.

879
01:34:11,188 --> 01:34:15,860
But don't worry, Paul.
I've prepared for what must be done.

880
01:34:16,861 --> 01:34:18,904
I put two bullets in my gun:

881
01:34:19,446 --> 01:34:22,408
One for you and one for me.

882
01:34:23,492 --> 01:34:26,245
Oh, darling, it'll be so beautiful.

883
01:34:45,556 --> 01:34:46,974
Now, don't be afraid.

884
01:34:48,934 --> 01:34:50,477
I love you.

885
01:34:53,898 --> 01:34:55,608
I love you too.

886
01:34:58,485 --> 01:34:59,945
And you're right.

887
01:35:00,654 --> 01:35:02,907
We are meant to be together.

888
01:35:03,782 --> 01:35:05,784
And I know we must die.

889
01:35:07,578 --> 01:35:09,163
But it must be...

890
01:35:10,289 --> 01:35:12,374
...so that Misery can live.

891
01:35:14,043 --> 01:35:15,669
We have the power...

892
01:35:15,961 --> 01:35:19,006
...to give Misery eternal life.

893
01:35:20,341 --> 01:35:22,509
We must finish the book.

894
01:35:25,804 --> 01:35:27,765
But the time is now.

895
01:35:28,140 --> 01:35:30,017
Soon others will come.

896
01:35:31,352 --> 01:35:33,270
It's almost finished.

897
01:35:34,897 --> 01:35:36,148
By dawn...

898
01:35:37,650 --> 01:35:39,443
...we'll be able to give Misery...

899
01:35:40,903 --> 01:35:42,488
...back to the world.

900
01:36:05,219 --> 01:36:07,096
I'll fix you something to eat.

901
01:36:24,238 --> 01:36:29,034
Paul, I'm dying. Does she wind up
with Ian or Winthorne?

902
01:36:29,451 --> 01:36:31,036
You'll know very soon.

903
01:36:31,537 --> 01:36:33,956
I've just thought of the last chapter.

904
01:36:34,039 --> 01:36:35,082
You know...

905
01:36:35,833 --> 01:36:40,296
...when I finish, I'd like
everything to be perfect.

906
01:36:40,671 --> 01:36:42,047
I'll need three things.

907
01:36:42,881 --> 01:36:44,049
What things?

908
01:36:45,551 --> 01:36:46,760
You don't know?

909
01:36:48,887 --> 01:36:50,431
I was fooling, silly.

910
01:36:51,390 --> 01:36:52,391
You need a cigarette.

911
01:36:52,558 --> 01:36:56,228
You used to smoke, but you quit
except when you finish a book.

912
01:36:56,395 --> 01:37:00,149
And you have just one.
And the match is to light it.

913
01:37:00,357 --> 01:37:04,945
And you need one glass of champagne.
Dom Perignon.

914
01:37:05,738 --> 01:37:08,198
Dom Perignon it is.

915
01:37:27,760 --> 01:37:28,802
Annie?

916
01:37:32,598 --> 01:37:33,891
Yes, Paul.

917
01:37:35,934 --> 01:37:37,436
I'm almost done.

918
01:37:38,103 --> 01:37:40,773
Oh, Paul, this is so romantic.

919
01:37:40,939 --> 01:37:44,109
Ian and Winthorne dueling
for the right to Misery's hand.

920
01:37:44,318 --> 01:37:48,655
Does Ian win? Oh, don't tell me.
It's Winthorne, right?

921
01:37:48,947 --> 01:37:51,158
You'll know everything in a minute.

922
01:37:51,825 --> 01:37:53,160
Get the champagne.

923
01:38:29,988 --> 01:38:31,448
Did I do good?

924
01:38:33,158 --> 01:38:34,660
You did perfect.

925
01:38:37,121 --> 01:38:38,497
Except for one thing.

926
01:38:40,332 --> 01:38:43,502
This time we'll need two glasses.

927
01:38:44,545 --> 01:38:46,463
Oh, Paul.

928
01:39:21,457 --> 01:39:25,294
Remember how for years nobody knew
who Misery's real father was...

929
01:39:25,836 --> 01:39:27,713
...or if they'd ever be reunited?

930
01:39:28,422 --> 01:39:29,673
It's all right here.

931
01:39:29,882 --> 01:39:33,510
Does she finally marry Ian,
or will it be Winthorne?

932
01:39:34,094 --> 01:39:35,637
It's all right here.

933
01:39:38,390 --> 01:39:39,808
Paul, you can't!

934
01:39:40,476 --> 01:39:41,477
Why not?

935
01:39:41,685 --> 01:39:43,395
I learned it from you.

936
01:39:44,980 --> 01:39:46,273
No, no, no!

937
01:39:46,482 --> 01:39:49,568
Not Misery! Not my Misery!

938
01:39:50,194 --> 01:39:51,904
Not my Misery!

939
01:40:04,208 --> 01:40:06,919
I'm gonna kill you, you lying cocksucker!

940
01:40:46,166 --> 01:40:47,960
Here, you want it?! You want it?!

941
01:40:48,126 --> 01:40:50,837
Eat it! Eat it till you choke...

942
01:40:51,046 --> 01:40:53,882
...you sick, twisted fuck!

943
01:42:47,204 --> 01:42:50,540
This is it. The very first copy.

944
01:42:50,749 --> 01:42:53,627
The word I'm getting is the Times
review is gonna be a love letter.

945
01:42:53,835 --> 01:42:55,170
That'll be a first.

946
01:42:55,379 --> 01:42:58,423
And my contacts at Time and Newsweek
tell me they're both raves.

947
01:42:58,632 --> 01:43:02,260
Don't laugh, but for the first time,
you've got a shot at prizes.

948
01:43:02,719 --> 01:43:03,845
Great.

949
01:43:04,429 --> 01:43:08,225
I thought you'd be thrilled.
You're being taken seriously.

950
01:43:08,433 --> 01:43:12,479
I'm delighted the critics like it,
and I hope the people like it too...

951
01:43:14,481 --> 01:43:15,941
...but I wrote it for me.

952
01:43:16,441 --> 01:43:18,985
Now, don't think
I'm completely nuts, but...

953
01:43:20,696 --> 01:43:24,908
...in some way Annie Wilkes...

954
01:43:25,534 --> 01:43:27,452
...that whole experience...

955
01:43:28,787 --> 01:43:29,788
...helped me.

956
01:43:31,164 --> 01:43:33,959
Paul, since you brought her up,
I have to ask...

957
01:43:34,167 --> 01:43:36,628
...or I'll be drummed out
of the agent's union.

958
01:43:36,837 --> 01:43:40,424
How would you feel about a nonfiction
book about what went on in that house?

959
01:43:40,632 --> 01:43:43,093
If I didn't know you better
I'd think you suggested...

960
01:43:43,301 --> 01:43:46,680
...I dredge up the worst horror of my
life so we could make a few bucks.

961
01:43:48,515 --> 01:43:50,100
I thought you were over it.

962
01:43:50,308 --> 01:43:53,645
I don't know if anyone could ever
totally get over something like that.

963
01:43:54,146 --> 01:43:55,272
It's weird.

964
01:43:57,149 --> 01:43:59,109
Even though I know she's dead...

965
01:44:00,819 --> 01:44:03,572
...I still think about her
once in a while.

966
01:44:03,947 --> 01:44:07,409
Excuse me. I don't mean to bother
you, but are you Paul Sheldon?

967
01:44:07,993 --> 01:44:08,994
Yes.

968
01:44:09,494 --> 01:44:12,122
I just want to tell you
I'm your number one fan.

969
01:44:13,165 --> 01:44:15,292
That's very sweet of you.

